Response to
Episode 10 - "The Electric Boy"
@-------------------------------------------------
- Batteries back then were so much bigger than the batteries today. (Back then they took up multiple square feet of room while today they are the size of a pinkie). This somehow made me think to something similar that I learned last year in CS class with Ms. Genkina. She talked to us how some years ago, storage disks for computers were huge. Like companies had to have an entire room dedicated to the storage drives for their computers. Thanks to today's technology, there are smaller Hard Disk Drives and even Solid State Drives which can store a lot more data and are a lot smaller in proportion to the storage drives back then.
- Michael Faraday honestly sounds like a very humble man to me. He had memory problems and even depression but still contibuted so much to the scientific world with his findings about electrictromagnetism and light.
- The explanation about how light works reminded me of chemistry class last year. I remember learning about light acting as both a wave and a particle and how it was connected to the schrodinger's cat paradox. It says that a person cannot know for sure if the cat inside the box with the atom has died unless he/she looks inside of the box. So in the person's perspective before the box is opened, the cat is both dead and alive, and only one of those becomes truth once the box is opened.
